field.value:
I create a component with inspectionBehavior="declaredonly", but it's property gets assigned by Windsor even if I do not explicitly specifiy in the config. Here is a little example

{code lang=java}
public interface ILogger
{
    void LogDebug(String message);
}

public class DevNullLogger : ILogger
{
    public static ILogger Instance = new DevNullLogger();

    public void LogDebug(string message)
    {
    }
}

public class AlertManager
{
    private ILogger mLogger = DevNullLogger.Instance;

    public ILogger Logger
    {
        get { return mLogger; }
        set { mLogger = value; }
    }

    public void Alert(String message)
    {
        mLogger.LogDebug(String.Format("Alert send {0} message", message));
    }
}
{code}
I mapped this component in this way.

{code lang=xml}
<component id="Log4NetLogger" service="IoC.ILogger, IoC" type="IoC.Log4netLogger, IoC" lifestyle="Singleton">
</component>
<component id="AlertManager" service="IoC.AlertManager, IoC" type="IoC.AlertManager, IoC" lifestyle="Transient" inspectionBehavior="declaredonly">
   <parameters>
   </parameters>
</component>
{code}
I expect that the Logger property will be not touched by windsor, but at runtime I see that windsor assign the Log4Net logger to my alertManager instances.

Alk.
